1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:15,184
In this Education Tips report, we explore ways to use the VOA Learning English website for listening activities to help students learning American English.

2
00:00:15,184 --> 00:00:28,872
While these activities require an Internet connection in the planning stage, most do not require you to use the internet in the classroom.

3
00:00:28,872 --> 00:00:38,291
For example, the text from our written series can be printed and read aloud to students.

4
00:00:38,291 --> 00:00:47,336
You can read more about materials needed for each activity by downloading the printable guide.

5
00:00:47,336 --> 00:00:55,213
Now, let’s start with two activities for beginning English learners.

6
00:00:55,213 --> 00:01:09,171
For the first activity, you can use audio from our popular culture program, What’s Trending Today, or the news-related stories from As It Is.

7
00:01:09,171 --> 00:01:16,709
Or try using a video from News Words, a series about terms in the news.

8
00:01:16,709 --> 00:01:21,757
Before the activity, choose your audio or video.

9
00:01:21,757 --> 00:01:28,888
Also, develop three to four questions to test listener understanding.

10
00:01:28,888 --> 00:01:35,707
To begin the activity, divide students into groups of three or four.

11
00:01:35,707 --> 00:01:43,192
Hand out the questions for the story or write them on a board or shared screen.

12
00:01:43,192 --> 00:01:52,355
Ask the students to read the questions before listening to the audio or watching the video.

13
00:01:52,355 --> 00:01:56,184
Then, play the video or recording.

14
00:01:56,184 --> 00:02:01,992
Have each group work together on the answer to one question.

15
00:02:01,992 --> 00:02:05,976
They should write complete sentence answers.

16
00:02:05,976 --> 00:02:11,501
Set a limit of no more than three sentences per question.

17
00:02:11,501 --> 00:02:17,987
Then, have each group share their answers to the questions with the class.

18
00:02:17,987 --> 00:02:28,088
Another group listening activity for beginning English learners uses the video series Let’s Learn English.

19
00:02:28,088 --> 00:02:34,171
For this activity, teachers will need response paddles.

20
00:02:34,171 --> 00:02:45,312
These interactive paddles were developed by Bill Pellowe and Paul Shimizu, two professors based in Japan.

21
00:02:45,312 --> 00:02:56,405
You can click on the image of the paddles for a downloadable version that you can print, copy, and give to students.

22
00:02:56,405 --> 00:03:01,832
For more details, download the printable guide.

23
00:03:01,832 --> 00:03:09,821
Before the activity, choose the Let’s Learn English episode you plan to show.

24
00:03:09,821 --> 00:03:16,064
To begin, divide students into pairs -- groups of two.

25
00:03:16,064 --> 00:03:21,221
Play the main video at the top of the page.

26
00:03:21,221 --> 00:03:28,813
After playing the video, show the online quiz on the shared screen.

27
00:03:28,813 --> 00:03:37,917
For each question, play the video and then let students discuss their answers.

28
00:03:37,917 --> 00:03:46,768
Then, ask them to raise their response paddles to show which answers they chose.

29
00:03:46,768 --> 00:03:52,931
For more on this activity, download the printable guide.

30
00:03:52,931 --> 00:04:00,667
Now, let’s explore activities for intermediate level English learners.

31
00:04:00,667 --> 00:04:19,440
For this activity, you can choose from a wide variety of English learning series, such as English in a Minute, English at the Movies, Words and Their Stories and Personal Technology.

32
00:04:19,440 --> 00:04:27,125
In addition, many of the As It Is stories are perfect for intermediate learners.

33
00:04:27,125 --> 00:04:37,363
Before the activity, choose the video or audio you’d like to use and prepare five questions about the material.

34
00:04:37,363 --> 00:04:42,245
To begin, divide students into five groups.

35
00:04:42,245 --> 00:04:47,331
Pairs will work well if the class has 10 students or less.

36
00:04:47,331 --> 00:04:55,171
Hand out copies of the questions or write them on the board or shared screen.

37
00:04:55,171 --> 00:05:01,285
Ask each group to be responsible for answering one question.

38
00:05:01,285 --> 00:05:09,813
If the class is large, two groups can answer one question and compare their answers.

39
00:05:09,813 --> 00:05:21,872
For another activity, intermediate level learners can turn to our Health & Lifestyle and Science in the News series.

40
00:05:21,872 --> 00:05:28,517
Before the activity, choose the story you would like to use.

41
00:05:28,517 --> 00:05:46,304
You may notice that some health and science reports seem more complex than others; some may be better for intermediate activities, while others are better for advanced activities.

42
00:05:46,304 --> 00:05:52,765
To begin the activity, organize students into small groups.

43
00:05:52,765 --> 00:06:03,061
Play the audio or have one or two students take turns reading parts of the story text aloud.

44
00:06:03,061 --> 00:06:08,856
Afterward, show the online quiz on the shared screen.

45
00:06:08,856 --> 00:06:17,592
Ask students to raise their response paddles to show which options they chose.

46
00:06:17,592 --> 00:06:25,080
Now, let’s look at two activities for advanced learners.

47
00:06:25,080 --> 00:06:37,632
The VOA Learning English programs People in America and American Stories also come with online quizzes.

48
00:06:37,632 --> 00:06:45,819
In addition, American Stories also comes with a detailed, downloadable lesson plan each week.

49
00:06:45,819 --> 00:06:52,619
For the first activity, organize students into pairs or small groups.

50
00:06:52,619 --> 00:06:58,077
Play the video or audio for the program you have chosen.

51
00:06:58,077 --> 00:07:03,904
Then, show the online quiz on a shared screen.

52
00:07:03,904 --> 00:07:11,659
For each question, have students raise their response paddles to show the answers they chose.

53
00:07:11,659 --> 00:07:19,717
For details on additional listening activities for the two series, download the printable guide.

54
00:07:19,717 --> 00:07:33,323
Our series Health & Lifestyle and Science in the News can also be useful as group listening activities for advanced-level English learners.

55
00:07:33,323 --> 00:07:44,269
Remember that some of these stories work well for advanced learners, while others are better for intermediate learners.

56
00:07:44,269 --> 00:07:51,037
Before the activity, choose the story you’d like to use.

57
00:07:51,037 --> 00:07:58,437
To begin the activity, organize students into pairs or small groups.

58
00:07:58,437 --> 00:08:07,080
Play the audio or ask one or two volunteers to read the story aloud.

59
00:08:07,080 --> 00:08:12,363
Then, display the quiz on a shared screen.

60
00:08:12,363 --> 00:08:21,445
Ask student to raise their response paddles to show which answers they chose.

61
00:08:21,445 --> 00:08:28,880
After the quiz, there are additional learner-centered activities you can do.

62
00:08:28,880 --> 00:08:32,488
For example, you can:

63
00:08:32,488 --> 00:08:40,368
Have students pretend to question a scientist or health expert about the subject of the story.

64
00:08:40,368 --> 00:08:46,301
Write a letter or 'call' the main scientist named in the report.

65
00:08:46,301 --> 00:08:52,731
Ask a question or give advice related to the subject of the story.

66
00:08:52,731 --> 00:08:59,824
Create a word web of the main terms you need to know to understand the story.

67
00:08:59,824 --> 00:09:03,848
Take the story a few years into the future.

68
00:09:03,848 --> 00:09:07,667
How will this affect the average person?

69
00:09:07,667 --> 00:09:18,989
What developments do you predict will take place as a result of this scientific research or breakthrough in health understanding?

70
00:09:18,989 --> 00:09:28,715
Tell a story or write a 'news' story on the same issue as it would be treated 10 years in the future.

71
00:09:28,715 --> 00:09:41,120
In coming weeks, we will look at more on creative ways to use our website for classroom or group practice activities.

72
00:09:41,120 --> 00:09:50,077
You can find those reports and others on learningenglish.voanews.com.

73
00:09:50,077 --> 00:10:03,675
And, don’t forget to download the printable, extended guide of activities and directions by clicking on the document below or to the right of the page.

74
00:10:03,675 --> 00:10:05,653
I’m Jill Robbins.

75
00:10:05,653 --> 00:10:08,041
And I'm Alice Bryant.